<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="534" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is a new record of the species from the Indian subcontinent. This species forms a group with 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiller" authorityName="Stiller" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nicolaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaffectus">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,260,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">inaffectus</emphasis>
Stiller
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiller" authorityName="Stiller" box="[349,580,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nicolaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispinatus">
<emphasis box="[349,368,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[382,502,728,751]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">trispinatus</emphasis>
Stiller
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[640,766,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nicolaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serratus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[640,659,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[674,766,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">serratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[773,863,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[773,863,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having a partially sclerotized elongate aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">
The species shows variation in the shape of the head among the specimens from Shillong and Karnataka. Both male and female from Karnataka have a longer and more pointed crown (
<figureCitation box="[981,1041,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1583,1606]" captionTargetBox="[247,1334,206,1552]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[235,1353,193,1563]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Species of Nicolaus. 1 &amp; 2. N. abuensis sp. nov., female; 3 &amp; 4. N. bidentatus sp. nov., male; 5 &amp; 6. N. cornutus sp. nov., male; 7 – 10. Nicolaus bihamatus Xing &amp; Li: 7 &amp; 8. Female from Mudigere; 9 &amp; 10. Male from Shillong." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/228653/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">
Fig. 
<number box="[1027,1041,836,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) than the male from Shillong (Fig. 
<number box="[151,167,872,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" value="9.0">9</number>
). The specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[424,482,871,896]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[537,632,871,896]" name="Pakistan" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
also show some variation in the structure of male genitalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 28 – 40" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1788,1811]" captionTargetBox="[236,1361,346,1752]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[225,1362,330,1767]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 28 – 40. Nicolaus bihamatus Xing &amp; Li: 28. Head and thorax; 29. Face; 30. Male pygofer, lateral view (India); 31. Caudal region of pygofer, lateral view (India); 32 &amp; 33. Variation in caudal region of pygofer, lateral view (Pakistan); 34. Connective, style, valve and subgenital plate, dorsal view (India); 35. Connective and aedeagus, ventroposterior view (India); 36 &amp; 37. Lateral &amp; latero-ventral views of aedeagus (India); 38 &amp; 39. Variations in the distal apices of preatrial processes (Pakistan); 40. Female seventh sternite, mutilated along the hatched lines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/228656/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">
Figs 
<number box="[1366,1436,872,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" value="32.0" valueMax="33.0" valueMin="31.0">31–33</number>
and 
<number box="[203,274,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="534" value="38.5" valueMax="39.0" valueMin="38.0">38–39</number>
</figureCitation>
) and differ from typical specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[766,833,908,933]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="534">China</collectingCountry>
in the pygofer processes being internal rather than external, the slightly broader aedeagal shaft in ventral view and in the shape of the distal part of the preatrial processes. Therefore, identification of these specimens is tentative.
</paragraph>
